                        >

                        <p class="tpr-article-content__paragraph tpr-article-content__paragraph--blog">"Freedom on Fire should be screened three times a day, every day" - Dr Natalia Tronenko, the Co-Founder of British-Ukrainian Aid.</p>

                        <p class="tpr-article-content__paragraph tpr-article-content__paragraph--blog">It's an honour to work with Oscar-nominated director Evgeny Afineevsky and Emmy-nominated producer Shahida Tulaganova on Freedom of Fire: Ukraine's Fight for Freedom, the companion piece to Afineevsky's Academy Award-nominated documentary Winter on Fire.</p>
                        
                        <p class="tpr-article-content__paragraph tpr-article-content__paragraph--blog">This sweeping anti-war film is a testament to the Ukrainian people's resilience, opening with a packed stand-up comedy event hosted in an underground bunker. Documented across the span of a year and filmed by over 40 cinematographers across 20 Ukrainian cities, Freedom of Fire amplifies the views of the Ukrainian people - children, mothers, soldiers, doctors, artists, volunteers, clergymen and journalists - who are transformed as they witness ceaseless destruction and bloodshed.</p>

                        <p class="tpr-article-content__paragraph tpr-article-content__paragraph--blog">The film has been acclaimed at festivals internationally, following its world premiere at Venice and Toronto, and has been praised by Pope Francis following a special screening at the Vatican.</p>

                        

